HANTAVIRUS - AMERICAS (26): CANADA (ALBERTA)
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 13 Jun 2019 2:59 PM MDT
Source: Calgary TV News [edited]
https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/confirmed-alberta-hantavirus-cases-prompts-ahs-to-issue-warning-1.4465402


Albertans who may potentially encounter mice or mice droppings are encouraged to take precautionary measures following confirmed cases of a potentially fatal illness.

Alberta Health Services confirms there have been 2 cases of hantavirus [infection], an illness that affects the respiratory system, in Alberta this year [2019]. In the previous 5 years, there were 15 confirmed cases of hantavirus [infections] including one that proved fatal.

Humans can contract the virus by breathing in urine or feces particles from infected rodents.

To prevent the likelihood of contracting hantavirus, AHS encourages Albertans to take proactive measures when cleaning areas where mice droppings may be found including:
- ventilate potentially infected areas for 30 minutes prior to cleaning;
- wear rubber gloves;
- soak droppings, dead mice, and mouse nests with a solution of 9 parts water to 1 part bleach (allow solution to soak for 5 minutes);
- mop droppings or pick them up with paper towels and seal them in a bag;
- avoid vacuuming mouse droppings as there is the potential for creating hantavirus-containing dust.

Anyone who develops flu-like symptoms after encountering a potentially contaminated area is encouraged to seek medical assistance immediately.

[Byline: Ryan White]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
