[The report above does not state if the 2 cases developed hantavirus cardiopulmonary syndrome (HPS), which can develop quickly and sometimes is fatal. The report does not indicate the circumstances under which the infection was acquired, nor the specific hantavirus involved in the cases. Sin Nombre virus is most likely the hantavirus responsible for these cases. This report is another reminder that closed buildings that have been little used or unused over winter often provide habitats for deer mice and become sites for human exposure to Sin Nombre virus when dust is raised during cleaning. Although Sin Nombre virus infections with hantavirus pulmonary syndrome are relatively rare, the risk of death is significant.

A US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) site with extensive information about hantaviruses, including those in North America, with clinical signs, treatment, and epidemiology can be accessed at http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/diseases/hanta/hps/. An image of the deer mouse, _Peromyscus maniculatus_, can be accessed at https://mammals.carnegiemnh.org/pa-mammals/deer-mouse-peromyscus-maniculatus/.

The deer mouse is one of the most common and widely distributed mammals in North America and occurs in Alberta. A map showing its distribution can be accessed at https://www.discoverlife.org/nh/tx/Vertebrata/Mammalia/Cricetidae/Peromyscus/maniculatus/images/Peromyscus_maniculatus_map.320.jpg.html. - Mod.TY

